  <h2>Bel Aire's Market: Northeast Suburb with Solid Ranch Base</h2>
  <p>Bel Aire is northeast of Wichita, incorporated separately, about 8,000 people. It's got a lot of 1960s-1980s ranch homes — solid, affordable, not fancy but good bones. Some newer construction in recent decades, but the character is definitely the established ranch neighborhoods. Price range is $130k-$250k. More affordable than Andover, closer to Wichita than rural areas, good value for working families and retirees.</p>
  <p>Bel Aire sellers are often longtime owners ready to downsize, people inheriting properties, or landlords managing rentals. Less growth-driven than the west side suburbs, more stable and established.</p>

  <h2>Bel Aire Housing Market: Ranch Homes and Stability</h2>
  <p>Bel Aire's dominated by 1960s-1980s ranch construction — modest, well-built, aging but solid. Some newer builds have come in, but the character is definitely the older ranch homes. Price range is $130k-$250k. These are not fancy homes — they're practical family homes, blue-collar suburbs, good neighborhoods without pretension. Newer construction is there but not the majority.</p>
  <p>The market is steady rather than hot. Less turnover than growth suburbs like Maize or Goddard, but consistent. When someone sells, it's usually a real reason — downsizing, inheritance, landlord exit.</p>

  <h2>Who I Buy From in Bel Aire</h2>
  <p>Longtime owners ready to downsize into retirement. Heirs inheriting ranch homes from parents. Landlords managing rental properties who want to exit. Working-class homeowners facing financial pressure or life changes. People downsizing from larger homes to simplify. Estate sales from original Bel Aire buyers. Occasionally divorces where the home needs fast liquidation.</p>

